<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One small problem with that bluff was that, be=
fore the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33617633.=
284401/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTEt=
MjAvd2hvLWNvbnRyb2xzLW9wZW5haT9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMjA3MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWV=
kaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzEyMDcmdXRtX2NhbX=
BhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC06196090" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  Sam Altm=
an drama</a>, OpenAI=E2=80=99s employees were about to be able to sell some=
 of their shares of OpenAI stock at an <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/33617633.284401/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcG=
luaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTEtMjcvb3BlbmFpLWlzLXN0aWxsLWFuLTg2LWJpbGxpb24tb=
m9ucHJvZml0P2NtcGlkPUJCRDEyMDcyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRt=
X3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMTIwNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHV=
mZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe1109645" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  $86 billion valuation</a>.=
 Presumably if they all left for Microsoft, (1) they might=C2=A0forfeit the=
ir stock? and (2) the stock would be worthless anyway, so the tender would =
be off. They had powerful reasons of self-interest to stay and make the bes=
t of things. Though maybe Microsoft would have made them whole? In some sen=
se, if all of OpenAI=E2=80=99s employees left to run OpenAI-in-Exile at Mic=
rosoft, that would be like Microsoft <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/33617633.284401/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5jb20vMjAyMy9v=
cGVuYWlzLW1pc2FsaWdubWVudC1hbmQtbWljcm9zb2Z0cy1nYWluLw/607f07ceef4b8524a319=
a23cB0251a45c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bl=
ank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;"> acquiring OpenAI for free</a>; the least it could d=
o would be give the employees some shares. But then Altman came back, every=
thing is fine, the tender is apparently still going ahead, the employees ge=
t paid.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is striking that there are startups with (1=
) valuations in the tens of billions of dollars, (2) employees who have own=
ed stock for a while and would like to be cashed out, and (3) investors cla=
moring to buy that stock from them.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CPrivate markets are the new public ma=
rkets,=E2=80=9D I like to say around here: In modern markets, you can be a =
huge household-name company and raise billions of dollars from a wide range=
 of investors without ever going public. The main weakness of that claim in=
volves secondary liquidity: Public companies=E2=80=99 shareholders can easi=
ly sell stock, which means in particular that <em>employees=C2=A0</em>can t=
urn their stock-based compensation into cash; private companies=E2=80=99 sh=
areholders can=E2=80=99t just sell whenever they want to. But they want to.=
=C2=A0Employees do not have an infinite time horizon:=C2=A0They=E2=80=99d l=
ike to eventually be able to use their stock to buy a house. Venture capita=
l funds also do not have an infinite time horizon: They usually have to ret=
urn money to their own investors within 10 years or so. And so traditionall=
y private startups that get big and old enough eventually have to go public=
.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But we <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/33617633.284401/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGlua=
W9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTItMDQvd2hvc2UtaW5jb21lLWRvLXlvdS1wYXktdGF4ZXMtb24_=
Y21waWQ9QkJEMTIwNzIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5=
ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMxMjA3JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07cee=
f4b8524a319a23cB62de9dd1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" ta=
rget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; =
border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style=
: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  talked the other day</a> about venture =
capital continuation funds, which basically allow VC firms to sell their in=
vestments to themselves in a way that restarts the clock (and allows them t=
o recognize their gains).=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And now the employee tender has become somewha=
t standard. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/336176=
33.284401/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTItM=
DYvc3BhY2V4LXRlbmRlci1vZmZlci1zYWlkLXRvLXZhbHVlLXN0YXJ0dXAtYXQtMTc1LWJpbGxp=
b24tcGx1cz9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMjA3MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9=
zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzEyMDcmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1Zm=
Y/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc0726141" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  Bloomberg News reports</a>:<=
/p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Elon Musk=E2=80=99s SpaceX has initiated discu=
ssions about selling insider shares at a price that values the closely held=
 company at $175 billion or more, according to people familiar with the mat=
ter.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The most valuable US startup is discussing a t=
ender offer that could range from $500 million to $750 million, said some o=
f the people, who asked not to be identified because the information is con=
fidential. SpaceX is weighing offering shares at about $95 apiece, the peop=
le said.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Terms and the size of the tender offer could c=
hange depending on interest from both insider sellers and buyers.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A $175 billion valuation is a premium to the $=
150 billion valuation the company obtained through a tender offer this summ=
er. The increase would make SpaceX one of the world=E2=80=99s 75 biggest co=
mpanies by market capitalization, on par with T-Mobile USA Inc. ($179 billi=
on), Nike Inc. ($177 billion) and China Mobile ($176 billion), according to=
 data compiled by Bloomberg.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Nike=E2=80=99s stock trades about $800 million=
 per day, while SpaceX apparently does roughly three $750 million tender of=
fers a year.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-=
color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a> So,=C2=A0<em>less=C2=A0</em>liquid than public markets. But still bill=
ions of dollars a year of liquidity for employees and early investors to ca=
sh out. I assume SpaceX will eventually go public, and=C2=A0it is =E2=80=9C=
discussing an initial public offering for [its satellite internet business]=
 Starlink as soon as late 2024=E2=80=9D, though Elon Musk seems to genuinel=
y dislike=C2=A0public markets.=C2=A0But you could imagine a world in which =
people work their whole careers at SpaceX or OpenAI, they accumulate lots o=
f stock-based compensation, they cash out periodically by selling to second=
ary investors, they retire and cash out what=E2=80=99s left, and this all g=
oes on indefinitely without the companies ever going public. The financial =
technology is there to do that.</p>
