adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">The printer</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I was a young mergers-and-acquisitions lawyer =
at the tail end of the era of the financial printer. In the olden days, the=
 way that securities offerings (bond deals, initial public offerings, etc.)=
 and public-company mergers worked is that the bankers and lawyers would wr=
ite a securities document (the prospectus for an offering, the=C2=A0proxy s=
tatement for a merger) and negotiate it back and forth, and then when it wa=
s close to being done=C2=A0they would all go to the offices of a financial =
printer =E2=80=94=C2=A0a company like Donnelley Financial Solutions Inc.<a =
class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpar=
ent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0and finalize the document. The printer would inges=
t the draft Microsoft Word (or whatever) document into its own computers, a=
nd from then on the draft would live in the printer=E2=80=99s computers as =
a typeset document. And the printer would print out copies on oversized pap=
er, and the lawyers would sit in a conference room marking them up with pen=
s, and then the printer=E2=80=99s employees would take the markups and put =
the changes into=C2=A0the typeset document, and this would continue deep in=
to the night until the document was done and ready to be printed, filed wit=
h the US Securities and Exchange Commission and mailed to investors.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And for some reason there was beer? That proba=
bly lowered the quality of the proofreading. The printers were in a classic=
 agency-cost business: The company paid their fees, but the lawyers and ban=
kers generally told the company which printer to use, so the printers=E2=80=
=99 sales process involved taking young bankers and lawyers out to sporting=
 events and giving them good catering when they were at the printer all nig=
ht negotiating the document. For a while I had a Zagat=E2=80=99s guide embo=
ssed with the name of a financial printer, given=C2=A0to me as a marketing =
freebie. This was when there were Zagat=E2=80=99s guides!</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is all much less important now, because c=
omputers are better and it is easier to turn a draft Word document into a t=
ypeset PDF prospectus, or an =E2=80=9CEdgarized=E2=80=9D document ready to =
be filed on <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/336176=
33.284401/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9lZGdhci9hYm91dA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cB58a68066" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;"> the SEC=E2=80=99s filing system</a>, or a glossy prin=
ted prospectus, or all three, than it used to be.=C2=A0You don=E2=80=99t ha=
ve to spend all night at the printer's offices marking up paper copies, and=
 having a=C2=A0beer at the printer at 3 a.m. is no longer a rite of passage=
 for young bankers and lawyers. (After I was an M&amp;A lawyer, I was a con=
vertible bond underwriter, and I negotiated and edited many prospectuses wi=
thout setting foot in a printer=E2=80=99s office.) Still, you do need a PDF=
 prospectus, and you do need to file the prospectus with=C2=A0the SEC=E2=80=
=99s somewhat touchy and complicated Edgar system, and you probably even wa=
nt a printed prospectus to hand out to investors and board members, so ther=
e are still financial printers printing them. Here=E2=80=99s a fun <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33617633.284401/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9maW5hbmNlL2lwby1wcm9zcGVjdHVzLXB1YmxpYy1vZmZlcmluZy1pbnZl=
c3QtOGVmZTcxMTI_bW9kPWl0cF93c2o/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6dacf0a0" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 Wall Street Journal story about them</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Putting together the prospectus has long been =
a rite of passage for pre-IPO companies. For years, companies dutifully pri=
nted up thousands of copies for bankers to share as they made the rounds dr=
umming up investor interest.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Today, most of those meetings are virtual and =
companies print far fewer copies. While investors do pounce on newly filed =
prospectuses, most pluck out the key figures while skimming digital copies.=
 But the most boring book in the world lives on.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The business has been a moneymaker for the una=
ssuming printer that handles most of the jobs. Donnelley Financial Solution=
s, which did Arm=E2=80=99s printing job, says it has worked on prospectuses=
 for around 70% of all sizable U.S. IPOs over the past six years. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Donnelley=E2=80=99s services include formattin=
g and project management, and it is known among IPO lawyers for guiding com=
panies through the quirks and regulatory requirements that make for a smoot=
h filing with the SEC=E2=80=99s Edgar system.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the early aughts, a large technology compan=
y might print as many as 35,000 copies of its prospectus, according to Crai=
g Clay, president of global capital markets at Donnelley. The SEC stopped r=
equiring print copies in 2005, and these days around 100 copies is more sta=
ndard. That=E2=80=99s how many Arm printed, and those were given as keepsak=
es to executives, board members and advisers. A person close to Arm said on=
ly about 20% of the $900,000 cost went toward actual printing and that it p=
aid extra to have it completed over the holiday weekend.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Even as companies print fewer copies, the esti=
mated prospectus expenses, called =E2=80=9Cprinting fees and expenses=E2=80=
=9D or =E2=80=9Cprinting and engraving expenses=E2=80=9D on regulatory fili=
ngs, are holding relatively steady.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Much as IPOs have evolved from pure capital ra=
ises to marketing extravaganzas, the prospectus has evolved over the years =
from a nondescript black- (or blue-) and-white document to a company=E2=80=
=99s coming-out party.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s a way to take the regula=
tory requirement from the SEC and wrap it with some personality,=E2=80=9D s=
aid Clay. That includes paper versions=E2=80=94though the new designs come =
through on PDFs, too.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the old days the printer provided a place f=
or lawyers to haggle over commas; now it provides glossy photo spreads for =
startup founders.</p>
